<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Recognizes outstanding literary works as well as champions new writers.<br />
</em><em>Prize money: $1,000</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>(ART SEIDENBAUM AWARD FOR FIRST FICTION)</strong></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="135236" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-14-best-book-covers-of-march/71a2mh74k2l/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/71A2MH74K2L.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2550" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="K. M. Szpara, &lt;em&gt;Docile&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jamie Stafford-Hill (Tor.com, March 3)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;K. M. Szpara, &lt;em&gt;Docile&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Jamie Stafford-Hill (Tor.com, March 3)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/71A2MH74K2L-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/71A2MH74K2L-663x1024.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-135236 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love.jpeg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 183px) 100vw, 183px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love.jpeg 183w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love-33x50.jpeg 33w" alt="" width="183" height="276" data-attachment-id="135236" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=135236" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love.jpeg" data-orig-size="183,276" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Cinema Love" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Cinema-Love.jpeg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593474334" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Cinema Love</em></a> by Jiaming Tang</strong><br />
<strong>(Dutton)</strong></p>
<p>“There is much to admire in this intricately plotted novel. The depiction of Chinese immigrant life in America is very well done: rich in detail, and with lovely flashes of humour . . . And it’s a story with real heart: Tang shows genuine sympathy for each of his flawed characters as he carefully unpicks the moral complexities of their choices.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Claire Adam (<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/article/2024/jun/06/cinema-love-by-jiaming-tang-review-a-debut-with-real-heart" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Guardian</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Pemi Aguda, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781324065852" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Ghostroots</em></a> (W. W. Norton &amp; Company)<br />
Joseph Earl Thomas, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/god-bless-you-otis-spunkmeyer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>God Bless You, Otis Spunkmeyer</em></a> (Grand Central)<br />
Jessica Elisheva Emerson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781640097308" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Olive Days</em></a> (Counterpoint)<br />
Julian Zabalbeascoa, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781953387264" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>What We Tried to Bury Grows Here</em></a> (Two Dollar Radio)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>(FICTION)</strong></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="130713" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/50-fictional-booksellers-ranked/screen-shot-2020-01-23-at-12-23-12-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM.png" data-orig-size="800,345" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Screen Shot 2020-01-23 at 12.23.12 PM" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM-300x129.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM.png" class="size-medium wp-image-130713 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-1357x2048.jpg 1357w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend.jpg 1400w" alt="Say Hello to My Little Friend" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="130713" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/5-reviews-you-need-to-read-this-week-4-4-2024/say-hello-to-my-little-friend/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2113" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Say Hello to My Little Friend" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-678x1024.jpg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/say-hello-to-my-little-friend/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Say Hello to My Little Friend</em></a> by Jennine Capó Crucet</strong><br />
<strong>(Simon &amp; Schuster)</strong></p>
<p>“The miracle is not that <em>Say Hello to My Little Friend</em> works, so much as that it enlarges our sense of the possible, recalling the vanity of human aspiration not through a lens of ridicule but through one of empathy. The chorus of voices, the point-of-view shifts—all of it allows Crucet to imagine her way to a larger authenticity … Crucet insists that we rethink our models for engagement, with one another and with the world at large.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—David L. Ulin (<a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2024/04/say-hello-to-my-little-friend-jennine-capo-crucet/677942/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Atlantic</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Rita Bullwinkel, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/headshot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Headshot</em></a> (Viking)<br />
Percival Everett, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/james/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>James</em></a> (Doubleday)<br />
Miranda July, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/all-fours/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>All Fours</em></a> (Riverhead)<br />
Yuri Herrera, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/season-of-the-swamp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Season of the Swamp</em></a> (Graywolf)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>EDGAR AWARD</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Presented by the Mystery Writers of America, honoring the best in crime and mystery fiction.</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="135237" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-14-best-book-covers-of-march/81ccusymwgl/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/81cCUsymWgL.jpg" data-orig-size="1700,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jane Hirshfield, &lt;em&gt;Ledger&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by John Gall (Knopf, March 10)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jane Hirshfield, &lt;a href=&quot;https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780525657804&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ledger&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;; cover design by John Gall (Knopf, March)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/81cCUsymWgL-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/81cCUsymWgL-680x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-135237 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd-198x300.jpeg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd-198x300.jpeg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd.jpeg 297w" alt="The In Crowd" width="198" height="300" data-attachment-id="135237" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=135237" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd.jpeg" data-orig-size="297,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The In Crowd" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd-198x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-In-Crowd.jpeg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593685990" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The In Crowd</em></a> by Charlotte Vassell</strong><br />
<strong>(Vintage)</strong></p>
<p>“[A] smart, provocative novel … Vassell perfectly constructs a classic crime procedural against a backdrop of racism, sexism, and classism. Beauchamp is a winning character readers will adore … Readers don’t need to have read <em>The Other Half</em> to enjoy this intriguing novel, but reading both is as satisfying as pairing a cup of Earl Grey and a lavender biscuit. In the final pages, Vassell lays the groundwork for a third installment that promises to be as enjoyable as the ones that preceded it. A stellar sophomore outing for an intriguing detective.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—<em>Kirkus</em></p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Robert Jackson Bennett, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781984820716" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Tainted Cup</em></a> (Del Rey)<br />
Katrina Carrasco, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250371867" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Rough Trade</em></a> (Picador)<br />
Sarah Easter Collins, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593798355" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Things Don’t Break on Their Own</em></a> (Crown)<br />
Nicolás Ferraro, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781641296212" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>My Favorite Scar</em></a> (Soho Crime)<br />
Liz Moore, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-god-of-the-woods/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The God of the Woods</em></a> (Riverhead)<br />
Amy Tintera,<a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250880338" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em> Listen for the Lie</em></a> (Celadon)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>NEBULA AWARD</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Given each year by the Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America for the best science fiction or fantasy novel.</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="135238" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-14-best-book-covers-of-march/919rbkztu3l/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/919RBKZTu3L.jpg" data-orig-size="1539,2325" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mary South, &lt;em&gt;You Will Never Be Forgotten&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Alex Merto (FSG Originals, March 10)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/919RBKZTu3L-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/919RBKZTu3L-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-135238 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In-199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In.jpg 662w" alt="Someone You Can Build a Nest In" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="135238" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=135238" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Someone You Can Build a Nest In" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/Someone-You-Can-Build-a-Nest-In.jpg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780756419745" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Someone You Can Build a Nest In</em></a> by John Wiswell</strong><br />
<strong>(DAW)</strong></p>
<p>“This is a fast-paced and gloriously weird novel, full of explosive shenanigans and touching sentiment. It also manages to be an exploration of the queerness and the surprising fragility of monstrous bodies, as well as their resilience … a remarkably accomplished debut.”<i></i></p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Liz Bourke (<a href="https://locusmag.com/review/liz-bourke-reviews-someone-you-can-build-a-nest-in-by-john-wiswell/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><i>Locus Magazine</i></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Kerstin Hall, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250625441" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Asunder</em></a> (Tordotcom)<br />
Kelly Link, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-book-of-love/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Book of Love</em></a> (Random House/Ad Astra Press)<br />
Vajra Chandrasekera, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250847706" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Rakesfall</em></a> (Tordotcom)<br />
Yaroslav Barsukov, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781647101367" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Sleeping Worlds Have No Memory</em></a> (Caezik SF &amp; Fantasy)<br />
T. Kingfisher, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250244062" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>A Sorceress Comes to Call</em></a> (Tor Books)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>HUGO AWARD</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Awarded for the best science fiction or fantasy story of 40,000 words or more published in English or translated in the prior calendar year.</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-135239 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup-197x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup.jpg 658w" alt="" width="197" height="300" data-attachment-id="135239" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=135239" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="" data-image-title="The Tainted Cup" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Tainted-Cup.jpg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781984820716" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Tainted Cup</em></a> by Robert Jackson Bennett</strong><br />
<strong>(Del Rey)</strong></p>
<p>“Bennett’s newest, <em>The Tainted Cup</em>, absolutely rewards that attention: cleverly drawn characters and plots, a fascinating world with fantastic mechanics, and it manages to wrap up its narrative satisfyingly while leaving the door open for more.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Jake Casella (<a href="https://locusmag.com/review/jake-casella-brookins-reviews-the-tainted-cup-by-robert-jackson-bennett/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><i>Locus Magazine</i></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Adrian Tchaikovsky, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780316578974" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Alien Clay</em></a> (Orbit Books/Tor UK)<br />
Kaliane Bradley, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-ministry-of-time/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Ministry of Time</em></a> (Avid Reader Press/Sceptre)<br />
Adrian Tchaikovsky, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250290304" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Service Model</em></a> (Tordotcom)<br />
John Wiswell, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780756419745" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Someone You Can Build a Nest In</em></a> (DAW Books)<br />
T. Kingfisher, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781250244062" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>A Sorceress Comes to Call</em></a> (Tor Books)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><b>BRAM STOKER AWARD</b></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Presented by the Horror Writers Association for “superior achievement” in horror writing for novels.</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="135240" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-14-best-book-covers-of-march/norton_0310_our-revolution_ad-sarahmay-wilkinson_design-by-robin-billardello/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/NORTON_0310_Our-Revolution_AD-Sarahmay-Wilkinson_Design-by-Robin-Billardello-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1696,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="NORTON_0310_Our Revolution_AD Sarahmay Wilkinson_Design by Robin Billardello" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Honor Moore, &lt;em&gt;Our Revolution&lt;/em&gt;; cover design by Robin Bilardello, art direction by Sarahmay Wilkinson (W. W. Norton, March 10)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/NORTON_0310_Our-Revolution_AD-Sarahmay-Wilkinson_Design-by-Robin-Billardello-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/NORTON_0310_Our-Revolution_AD-Sarahmay-Wilkinson_Design-by-Robin-Billardello-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-135240 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood-198x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood.jpg 659w" alt="The Haunting of Velkwood" width="198" height="300" data-attachment-id="135240" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/?attachment_id=135240" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood.jpg" data-orig-size="659,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="" data-image-title="The Haunting of Velkwood" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/12/The-Haunting-of-Velkwood.jpg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668034248" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Haunting of Velkwood</em></a> by Gwendolyn Kiste</strong><br />
<strong>(S&amp;S/Saga Press)</strong></p>
<p>“…there comes a time when the label ‘rising star’ no longer applies, when an author achieves something that simply makes them a mainstay of the genre, a must-read storyteller whose imagination has developed into something towering. With <i>The Haunting of Velkwood</i>, Kiste has surely hit that mark, delivering a chilling character drama wrapped up in a high-concept horror narrative so ingenious that you might be jealous you never thought of it.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Matthew Jackson (<a href="https://www.pastemagazine.com/books/gwendolyn-kiste/the-haunting-of-velkwood-review-horror-fiction" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Paste</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Gabino Iglesias, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780316427012" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>House of Bone and Rain</em></a> (Mulholland Books)<br />
Stephen Graham Jones, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9781668022245" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>I Was a Teenage Slasher</em></a> (S&amp;S/Saga Press)<br />
Josh Malerman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593723142" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Incidents Around the House</em></a> (Del Rey)<br />
Paul G. Tremblay, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780063070011" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Horror Movie</em></a> (William Morrow)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>JOYCE CAROL OATES LITERARY PRIZE</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>An annual award presented by the New Literary Project to recognize mid-career writers of fiction.<br />
Prize Money: $50,000<br />
</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="130713" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/50-fictional-booksellers-ranked/screen-shot-2020-01-23-at-12-23-12-pm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM.png" data-orig-size="800,345" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Screen Shot 2020-01-23 at 12.23.12 PM" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM-300x129.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Screen-Shot-2020-01-23-at-12.23.12-PM.png" class="size-medium wp-image-130713 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-1357x2048.jpg 1357w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend.jpg 1400w" alt="Say Hello to My Little Friend" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="130713" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/5-reviews-you-need-to-read-this-week-4-4-2024/say-hello-to-my-little-friend/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2113" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Say Hello to My Little Friend" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/04/Say-Hello-to-My-Little-Friend-678x1024.jpg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/say-hello-to-my-little-friend/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Say Hello to My Little Friend</em></a> by Jennine Capó Crucet</strong><br />
<strong>(Simon &amp; Schuster)</strong></p>
<p>“There is something quixotic in watching Izzy spin himself and those around him into remakes of culture, but this, too, is true about the immigrant experience, which Capó Crucet details with breathtaking precision … [Capó Crucet] also has a rare knack for metanarrative, a skill that allows readers to think about Izzy’s story as a story without ruining its intimacy.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Eric A. Ponce (<a href="https://www.bookpage.com/reviews/say-hello-to-my-little-friend-jennine-capo-crucet-book-review/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>BookPage</em></a>)</p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-horse/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-131644 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f-199x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f-199x300.gif 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f.gif 429w" alt="The Horse Cover" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="131644" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/the-horse/the-horse-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f.gif" data-orig-size="429,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Horse Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f-199x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2024/07/5be73133493b6c3e17f4f3eeb3a87e2f.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-horse/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Horse</em></a> by Willy Vlautin</strong><br />
<strong>(Harper)</strong></p>
<p>“Vlautin’s gift for capturing the unique terror of the moment when heavy drinking turns to helplessness is rendered with heartbreaking acuity. Set against the desolate majesty of the high desert, Vlautin’s depiction of one broken soul trying to save another is aspirational, allegorical and, ultimately, transcendent.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Jim Ruland (<a href="https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2024-07-22/willy-vlautin-the-horse-book-review" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Los Angeles Times</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Sarah Manguso, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593241271" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Liars</em></a> (Hogarth)<br />
Julia Phillips, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/bear/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Bear</em></a> (Hogarth)<br />
Morgan Talty, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/fire-exit/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Fire Exit</em></a> (Tin House Books)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>GILLER PRIZE</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Given to a Canadian author of a novel or short story collection published in English (including translation) the previous year.<br />
Prize Money: $100,000 (winner), $10,000 (finalists)</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-134678 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6-194x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6-194x300.gif 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6-32x50.gif 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6.gif 419w" alt="Pick a Color" width="194" height="300" data-attachment-id="134678" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/pick-a-color/pick-a-color-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6.gif" data-orig-size="419,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Pick a Color Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6-194x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/405fdc1469b3c502408768e3d09e5ab6.gif" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/pick-a-color/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Pick a Color</em></a> by Souvankham Thammavongsa</strong><br />
<strong>(Little Brown and Company)</strong></p>
<p>“A feat of economy, unspooling Ning’s emotional journey amid the cage of her salon … Punches above its weight. Thammavongsa’s minimalism conveys a range of tones and psychological nuances as she grapples with the stubborn prejudices of class … Wily and caustic, the book condemns petty Western narcissisms yet allows for bursts of radiance.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">—Hamilton Cain (<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/books/2025/09/30/pick-a-color-souvankham-thammavongsa/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Washington Post</em></a>)</p>
<p><strong>Finalists:</strong></p>
<p>Mona Awad, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/we-love-you-bunny/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>We Love You, Bunny</em></a> (Marysue Rucci Books)<br />
Eddy Boudel Tan, <a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.ca/books/741704/the-tiger-and-the-cosmonaut-by-eddy-boudel-tan/9780735248557" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Tiger and the Cosmonaut</em></a> (Viking)<br />
Emma Donoghue, <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-paris-express/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Paris Express</em></a> (Summit)<br />
Emma Knight, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780593830451" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Life Cycle of the Common Octopus</em></a> (Pamela Dorman Books)</p>
							</div>
			<!-- <div class="share">
